The dataset consists of 831 brain MRI images used for binary classification of Parkinson’s Disease. The data is divided into two classes: Parkinson’s Disease (positive cases) and Normal (healthy controls). Each image represents a 2D axial MRI slice in grayscale format.

Multiple images belong to the same patient, and each file includes a patient identifier in its filename. This allows grouping of images at the patient level, which is important for preventing data leakage during training and evaluation.

During preprocessing, all images are resized to 224 × 224 pixels and converted from single-channel grayscale to three-channel format to match pretrained model requirements. Pixel values are normalized using standard ImageNet statistics.

To improve model generalization and handle the limited dataset size, several data augmentation techniques are applied during training, including random horizontal flipping, affine transformations, MixUp, CutMix, and Random Erasing.

A Stratified Group K-Fold strategy is used to ensure that images from the same patient do not appear in both training and validation sets, while also maintaining balanced class distribution across folds.
